snippet.textDisplay: I really don't get people who keep buying the newest  parts for their PCs as soon as they release. Once you've built your PC, if you've done your research, it should last you a few years before actually needing any kind of upgrades, maybe even a bit longer depending on what you're doing with it. You're essentially just losing money if you keep fanboying over a company, be it Intel or Ryzen in this case, and waste dollars on the newest flagship parts every year. It's just weird how sheepish people are to marketing. PC parts are becoming, or have become rather, the new smartphone market. Every year a new "super hyper ultra giga processor" gets released and people are just throwing their dollars at the screen because it's new hip thing to get. Even if you are building a PC at this current moment, I wouldn't buy these newest parts from either one of these companies. Just wait for the last year models to drop in price and get those. What ever it is that you're doing, most of you are probably playing games, these newest parts won't make your performance significantly better than the ones before these. Even if you do some serious processing in 3D or edit videos, you don't have to get the newest, most expensive parts. Be smart!

There were a few minutes of “seriousness” which was much better, but honestly I tuned out and stopped watching around the 10 minutes mark when the silliness started again.

Maybe I’m not the target demographic for this anymore, I just wanted to share why I’ve been skipping TL videos on my recommendations list recently and why I’ll be unsubscribing after trying to watch this.

snippet.textDisplay:
This is much better! Anthony's natural subzero chill allows him to be infinitely more comfortable than James was. James was a ball of nervous energy that didn't know what to do with himself. This fascinates me as I'd thought this might be the case for Anthony, too, despite his chill. (Is he just good at faking?) I mean, Anthony has always struck me as far more introverted than James, but the two don't necessarily go hand-in-hand. I admit, I'm introverted and I am also a ball of nervous energy, so... I might be biased in my thinking, there.

Anthony, how can you be so chill? Write self-help books!

This is a TalkLink I enjoyed, though. Whereas with the last one my autistic empathy dialled-up-to-11-because-my-dial-does-have-a-redundant-setting-that-ignores-the-logic-of-maxing-out-at-10-because-that's-far-too-sensible-for-anyone-riddled-with-anxiety-and-I'm-making-anyone-professionally-educated-in-English-have-a-seiz—anyway! Too much empathy. I felt so bad for James. I just felt so bad.

James did not want to be there. Give him a nice room he can hide in. I mean, it's what I'd want. Poor James. Actually felt really bad for him. I feel bad right now for feeling bad for him because I'm worried this seems patronising and it's going to turn into some horrible empathy-ception and everything is terrible.

ANTHONY THEN. He makes this work. Keep him around as a regular. I'll try to stop obsessing over how bad I felt for James. Was I traumatised? I don't know. Maybe. I'm acting like I was traumatised. Or TRIGGERED. That's what the youf say, isn't it? Haaa, oh dear. I guess... triggered. With an itchy trigger finger because that doesn't sound at all dirty. YES. I felt bad for James. Poor James.

Stick to those who feel comfortable in a social setting, whilst also being focused on by a camera lens. I'm glad I never have to do that. I'd end up sitting on my head and talking in tongues. Especially with how it can fluctuate between informative and horrible, awful, despicable, superficial small talk.

I LIKED THIS TALKLINKED. GOODBYE.

(Also, Google, fix your line-downs. Please. Thank you.)
